John Aman --the Amazing Man-- is clearing out a nest of vampires with his friend and famed fighter of paranormal threats Dr. Vampire when X-Bureau chief of operations Sylvia Manners (formerly known as the femme fatale "The Black Angel") arrives to inform him that his girlfriend (the investigative reporter Zoe Henderson) has gone missing.
name: How Sharper Than A Dragon's Tooth

description: X-Bureau agents Dan Garret --call sign "The Blue Beetle" -- and Diana Adams --call sign "Miss Masque" -- confront the escaped fugitive known as Rodent in an abandoned warehouse. But when the X-Bureau's fugitive recovery team arrives team leader Boom Boom Brannigan informs them that they're to join The Amazing Man (John Aman) on a new mission. Meanwhile Aman begins having second thoughts about his new X-Bureau allies.
name: X Marks The Spot

description:
Luck had been with the Convict Commandos since they had escaped from the Japanese in 1942. They had carried out the most perilous of missions with little more than bumps and bruises to show for it.

But luck has a habit of changing suddenly, especially when it is pushed, and it certainly changed for the Convict Commandos as they flew to their next target. They had passed through dangerous skies before, but none quite as dangerous as those over Arnhem.
name: Fatal Mission

description:
"Bandits ahead! Go! Go! Go!"

Time and again that staccato command unleashed the savage fighting spirit of Britain's Spitfire pilots, driving them to hurl their machines in slashing attack after attack against the Luftwaffe hordes in the only method of defence that they believed in - attack.

Go! Go! Go!

Note: Original released as Commando No 83 (Sept 1963).
name: Send For Spitfires

description:
In 1942, over Canada, the last thing that the pilots of the Fleet Air Arm expected to see was a hostile aircraft. After all, the nearest enemy base was thousands of miles away. But that was exactly what the FAA boys did see - for the Germans had constructed a carrier in secret and sailed it across the Atlantic to attack a vital Canadian port.

Though outnumbered and outgunned, the Fleet Air Arm Martlet and Swordfish aircraft were not going to go out without a fight, and that hulking German aircraft carrier looked like a good target…
name: "Sink the Wagner!"

description:
Slowly, painfully, the three RAF Hurricanes staggered through the desert sky, desperately striving to reach home and safety.

The wreck in the middle had a wounded pilot slumped over its controls, as near unconsciousness as makes no difference, and all that held his tattered plane in the air was the wingtips of his comrades' planes on either side.

Mile by mile they struggled on, grimly, gallantly - then came the sinister chatter of cannons and machine guns behind them. The Black Buzzard had arrived for a kill…

Note: Original released as Commando No 897 (December 1974) and it was re-issued as No 2187 (June 1988).
name: The Black Buzzard

description: Fantasy and comic artist Al Rio has made a solid reputation of outstanding work at top companies like Marvel, DC, Dark Horse, Image, Wildstorm, and others. While superheroes are fun to draw and it certainly pays the bills, Al's first love is the female form! In this first volume of private works, Rio demonstrates that fondness for the curves and bumps that make life so worth living in a collection of artwork that glows with tropical heat!
name: Volume One

description: Drop-dead gorgeous never looked so good! One of the most prolific and supremely talented artists working in comics today, Al Rio offers yet another showcase of fabulous babes, hot jungle queens, and various deadly femmes!
name: Volume Two
